spec.name: Level 32 - Option<T> Advanced
spec.message: Master advanced Option<T> techniques! Explore powerful combinators like flatten, filter, or_else, and zip. Learn to chain operations elegantly and handle complex nested Option scenarios.
spec.hint_message: Option methods: flatten() converts Option<Option<T>> to Option<T>. filter() applies predicate. or_else() provides lazy default. zip() combines Options. Use ? for early None returns.

spec.name: Level 26 - Smart Pointers - RefCell<T>
spec.message: Achieve interior mutability with RefCell<T>! RefCell allows you to mutate data even when there are immutable references to it, by moving borrow checking to runtime. Powerful but requires careful use!
spec.hint_message: RefCell<T>: Interior mutability pattern. borrow() returns Ref<T>, borrow_mut() returns RefMut<T>. Runtime borrow checking - panics on violations. Combine with Rc for shared mutable data.

spec.name: Level 7 - References & Borrowing
spec.message: Learn about References and Borrowing! Rust allows you to refer to values without taking ownership through references (&). This enables efficient memory usage while maintaining safety through borrowing rules.
spec.hint_message: References: &value creates immutable reference, &mut value creates mutable reference. Rules: 1) Any number of immutable refs OR one mutable ref, 2) References must always be valid, 3) No dangling references.

spec.name: Level 15 - Enums
spec.message: Explore algebraic data types with Enums! Unlike other languages, Rust enums can hold data in their variants. Master the powerful Option<T> and Result<T, E> enums that enable safe null and error handling.
spec.hint_message: Enums: 'enum Name { Variant1, Variant2(Type) }'. Variants can hold data: Some(T), None, Ok(T), Err(E). Use match to handle all variants safely. impl blocks can add methods to enums.

spec.name: Level 28 - Weak References
spec.message: Break reference cycles with Weak<T>! Weak references don't affect reference counting and can become invalid. Perfect for parent-child relationships and observer patterns where you need non-owning references.
spec.hint_message: Weak<T>: Non-owning reference. Rc::downgrade() creates Weak, weak.upgrade() returns Option<Rc<T>>. Doesn't affect strong_count. Use for back-references and breaking cycles.

spec.name: Level 36 - File I/O
spec.message: Master file operations in Rust! Learn to read, write, and manipulate files safely. Explore the std::fs module, Path and PathBuf, buffered I/O, and error handling for file operations.
spec.hint_message: File I/O: std::fs for file operations. File::open() for reading, File::create() for writing. BufReader/BufWriter for buffered I/O. Path/PathBuf for cross-platform paths. Always handle I/O errors!

spec.name: Level 50 - Final Project
spec.message: Congratulations! You've mastered Rust fundamentals! This final level challenges you to apply everything you've learned. Plan and build a complete project using advanced Rust concepts, best practices, and real-world patterns.
spec.hint_message: Final Project: Combine all concepts learned. Plan architecture, handle errors gracefully, write comprehensive tests, document your code, optimize performance. You're now a Rust programmer!

spec.name: Level 39 - Standard Input/Output
spec.message: Interact with users through standard I/O! Master stdin, stdout, and stderr. Learn buffered reading, flushing output, and building interactive command-line programs.
spec.hint_message: Standard I/O: stdin().read_line() for input, println! for stdout, eprintln! for stderr. Use io::stdout().flush() to force output. BufReader for efficient line reading.

spec.name: Level 31 - Result<T, E> Deep Dive
spec.message: Deep dive into Result<T, E>! Master the many methods available: map, map_err, and_then, unwrap_or, unwrap_or_else. Learn to chain operations and transform both success and error values elegantly.
spec.hint_message: Result methods: map() transforms Ok values, map_err() transforms Err values. and_then() chains Results. unwrap_or() provides default. Use ? for early returns in functions returning Result.

spec.name: Level 48 - Async/Await Basics
spec.message: Enter asynchronous programming! Learn async/await syntax, the Future trait, and async runtimes like tokio. Build efficient concurrent programs without blocking threads.
spec.hint_message: Async/await: async fn returns Future, await keyword waits for completion. Need runtime like tokio. Non-blocking concurrency. join! runs futures concurrently, select! races them.

spec.name: Level 11 - Vectors (Vec<T>)
spec.message: Master Rust's most important collection: Vec<T>! Vectors are growable arrays allocated on the heap. Learn creation, manipulation, indexing, and iteration. Understand capacity vs length and ownership implications.
spec.hint_message: Vectors: Vec::new() or vec![] macro. Methods: push(), pop(), get(), len(). Index with [i] (panics) or get(i) (returns Option). for item in &vec iterates by reference.

spec.name: Level 40 - Serialization
spec.message: Convert data to and from different formats! Master the serde ecosystem for JSON, YAML, TOML, and binary serialization. Learn derive macros and custom serialization strategies.
spec.hint_message: Serialization: serde crate with Serialize/Deserialize derives. serde_json for JSON, bincode for binary. Use #[serde(rename)] for field mapping. Custom serializers for complex types.

spec.name: Level 18 - Associated Functions
spec.message: Learn functions that belong to types but don't take self! Associated functions are called with :: syntax and are perfect for constructors and utility functions. Master the 'new' convention and factory patterns.
spec.hint_message: Associated functions: No self parameter, called with Type::function(). Common pattern: fn new() -> Self for constructors. Use :: syntax, not . (dot). Great for factory methods and utilities.

spec.name: Level 37 - Command Line Arguments
spec.message: Build command-line applications! Learn to parse command-line arguments with std::env::args, validate input, and use libraries like clap for sophisticated argument parsing with automatic help generation.
spec.hint_message: Command line args: std::env::args() returns iterator. Skip first (program name). Use clap crate for advanced parsing with derives. Validate arguments and provide helpful error messages.

spec.name: Level 23 - References in Structs
spec.message: Store references in structs safely! When structs hold references, they need lifetime parameters to ensure the referenced data lives long enough. Master struct lifetime annotations and impl blocks.
spec.hint_message: Struct lifetimes: struct Name<'a> { field: &'a Type }. impl blocks need lifetimes too: impl<'a> Name<'a>. All references in struct must be valid for struct's lifetime.

spec.name: Level 47 - Concurrency - Channels
spec.message: Communicate between threads with channels! Master mpsc (multiple producer, single consumer) channels, learn about bounded vs unbounded channels, and explore advanced patterns with crossbeam.
spec.hint_message: Channels: mpsc::channel() creates sender/receiver pair. send() sends values, recv() receives. Channel closes when all senders dropped. crossbeam provides more channel types and select! macro.

spec.name: Level 46 - Concurrency - Threads
spec.message: Enter concurrent programming with threads! Learn thread::spawn, joining threads, moving data between threads safely, and sharing state with Mutex and Arc. Master Send and Sync traits.
spec.hint_message: Threads: thread::spawn() creates threads, join() waits for completion. move closures transfer ownership. Arc<Mutex<T>> for shared mutable state. Send/Sync traits ensure thread safety.

spec.name: Level 13 - Iterators
spec.message: Unlock the power of functional programming with Iterators! Learn lazy evaluation, iterator adaptors (map, filter, enumerate), and consuming adaptors (collect, fold, reduce). Master zero-cost abstractions!
spec.hint_message: Iterators: .iter() for &T, .into_iter() for T, .iter_mut() for &mut T. Adaptors: map(), filter(), enumerate() are lazy. Consumers: collect(), fold(), for_each() trigger evaluation.

spec.name: Level 16 - Advanced Pattern Matching
spec.message: Master advanced pattern matching! Go beyond basic match expressions. Learn destructuring, guard clauses, range patterns, @ bindings, reference patterns, and convenient if let / while let constructs.
spec.hint_message: Advanced patterns: Destructure structs/tuples in match. Guards: 'Some(x) if x > 5'. Ranges: '1..=10'. @ bindings: 'Some(x @ 1..=5)'. if let for single pattern, while let for loops.

spec.name: Level 41 - Traits Basics
spec.message: Enter the world of Traits - Rust's approach to shared behavior! Define common functionality that multiple types can implement. Learn trait bounds, default implementations, and derive macros.
spec.hint_message: Traits: Define shared behavior with 'trait Name { fn method(&self) }'. Implement with 'impl TraitName for Type'. Use trait bounds: 'fn func<T: Trait>(x: T)'. Derive common traits with #[derive(...)].

spec.name: Level 12 - HashMaps
spec.message: Learn key-value storage with HashMap<K, V>! HashMaps provide fast lookups using hash tables. Master insertion, access, updates, and the powerful Entry API for complex operations.
spec.hint_message: HashMaps: HashMap::new(), insert(key, value), get(&key) returns Option<&V>. Entry API: entry(key).or_insert(default) for complex updates. Keys must implement Hash + Eq traits.

spec.name: Level 8 - Strings & String Literals
spec.message: Master Rust's string types! Learn the difference between &str (string slice) and String (owned string). Understand UTF-8 encoding, string methods, and when to use each type for efficient string handling.
spec.hint_message: String types: &str is immutable string slice, String is growable owned string. Use String::from() or .to_string() to convert. String slices (&str) are more efficient for read-only operations.

spec.name: Level 42 - Trait Objects
spec.message: Achieve runtime polymorphism with trait objects! Use dyn Trait for dynamic dispatch, store different types in collections, and understand object safety rules. Master Box<dyn Trait> patterns.
spec.hint_message: Trait objects: dyn Trait enables runtime polymorphism. Box<dyn Trait> for owned, &dyn Trait for borrowed. Object-safe traits only (no generics, Self-sized). Use for heterogeneous collections.

spec.name: Level 45 - Operator Overloading
spec.message: Make your types feel native with operator overloading! Implement standard operators through traits like Add, Sub, Index, and Deref. Create intuitive APIs that feel natural to use.
spec.hint_message: Operator overloading: Implement traits like Add (+), Sub (-), Mul (*), Index ([]), Deref (*). std::ops module contains all operator traits. Makes custom types feel built-in.

spec.name: Level 19 - Modules & Crates
spec.message: Organize your code with Modules and Crates! Learn the module system, visibility rules (pub), path syntax (crate::, super::, self::), and how to structure large projects. Master the use keyword for imports.
spec.hint_message: Modules: 'mod name { }' creates module. pub makes items public. Paths: crate:: (root), super:: (parent), self:: (current). use brings items into scope. External crates in Cargo.toml.

spec.name: Level 3 - Data Types & Literals
spec.message: Master Rust's Scalar Data Types! 🔢 Navigate through obstacles to collect all 4 type examples. Learn about integers (i32, u64), floats (f32, f64), booleans (true/false), and Unicode chars. TO WIN: Collect integers_tip, floats_tip, booleans_tip, and chars_tip, then reach the goal. Rust's type system prevents runtime errors!
spec.hint_message: TYPE EXAMPLES: let x: i32 = 42; (signed integer), let y: f64 = 3.14; (float), let z: bool = true; (boolean), let c: char = '🦀'; (Unicode char). Type annotations help compiler catch errors early. Use scan() to see ahead through fog of war!

spec.name: Level 7 - Boolean Doors
spec.message: Boolean Doors Challenge! 🚪 Learn boolean literals by controlling doors. Navigate to collect items by opening/closing doors strategically. TO WIN: Stand on door tiles and use open_door(true) to open or open_door(false) to close them. Collect 'boolean_tip' item first, then reach 'goal_item'. Master true/false literals!
spec.hint_message: DOOR CONTROLS: Move onto a door tile (brown █), then use 'open_door(true);' to open it (becomes green |) or 'open_door(false);' to close it. Boolean literals in Rust are lowercase: true/false (not True/False like Python). These are the only two boolean values!

spec.name: Level 27 - Memory Leaks & Reference Cycles
spec.message: Understand Rust's weakness: Reference Cycles! While Rust prevents most memory leaks, Rc<RefCell<T>> can create cycles where references keep each other alive. Learn to detect and prevent them.
spec.hint_message: Reference cycles: A→B→A with Rc creates leak. Strong references keep data alive indefinitely. Use Weak references to break cycles. Parent-child relationships often need weak child→parent links.

spec.name: Level 4 - Functions
spec.message: Functions are fundamental in Rust! Learn about function syntax, parameters, and return values. Functions use 'fn' keyword and have strict type annotations for parameters and return values.
spec.hint_message: Function syntax: 'fn function_name(param: Type) -> ReturnType { body }'. The last expression in a function is the return value (no semicolon needed).

spec.name: Level 29 - Drop Trait
spec.message: Master resource cleanup with the Drop trait! Drop is called automatically when values go out of scope. Implement Drop for custom cleanup logic like closing files, freeing memory, or releasing locks.
spec.hint_message: Drop trait: impl Drop for Type { fn drop(&mut self) {} }. Called automatically at end of scope. Can't call drop() directly - use std::mem::drop() for early cleanup. Drop order: reverse of creation.

spec.name: Level 17 - Method Syntax
spec.message: Add behavior to your data with Method Syntax! Learn impl blocks, the three forms of self (&self, &mut self, self), method chaining, and how Rust's automatic dereferencing makes method calls convenient.
spec.hint_message: Methods: 'impl StructName { fn method(&self) {} }'. &self borrows, &mut self mutably borrows, self takes ownership. Use -> Self for chaining. Rust auto-dereferences for method calls.

spec.name: Level 22 - Lifetime Annotations
spec.message: Master explicit lifetime annotations! When the borrow checker can't infer lifetimes, you'll need to annotate them. Learn the 'a syntax, function signatures, and how to establish relationships between lifetimes.
spec.hint_message: Lifetime annotations: 'a, 'b syntax. Functions: fn func<'a>(x: &'a str) -> &'a str. Multiple lifetimes show relationships. Constraints: 'a: 'b means 'a outlives 'b.

spec.name: Level 38 - Environment Variables
spec.message: Configure applications with environment variables! Learn std::env functions, the dotenv crate for .env files, and best practices for configuration management and security.
spec.hint_message: Environment variables: env::var() gets variable, env::vars() gets all. Use dotenv for .env files. Provide defaults with unwrap_or(). Never log sensitive env vars!

spec.name: Level 10 - Structs
spec.message: Create custom data types with Structs! Group related data together into meaningful units. Learn about classic structs, tuple structs, and unit structs. Understand field access, instantiation, and update syntax.
spec.hint_message: Structs: 'struct Name { field: Type }' defines structure. Create with 'Name { field: value }'. Access fields with dot notation. Use struct update syntax ..other_instance to copy fields.

spec.name: Level 21 - Lifetimes
spec.message: Enter the most challenging concept in Rust: Lifetimes! Every reference has a lifetime - the scope for which it's valid. The borrow checker ensures references don't outlive the data they point to.
spec.hint_message: Lifetimes prevent dangling references. Borrow checker ensures borrowed data lives long enough. 'static lifetime lasts entire program. Most lifetimes are inferred (lifetime elision).

spec.name: Level 14 - Closures
spec.message: Master anonymous functions with Closures! Learn capture semantics, the three Fn traits (Fn, FnMut, FnOnce), and how closures enable powerful functional programming patterns. Understand move semantics!
spec.hint_message: Closures: |param| expr syntax. Capture by reference (default), mutable reference, or value (move). Fn traits: Fn (can call multiple times), FnMut (can mutate captures), FnOnce (consumes captures).

spec.name: Level 33 - Panic & Unwinding
spec.message: Understand Rust's panic mechanism! Learn when panics occur, how stack unwinding works, and techniques like catch_unwind. Master the balance between panicking and returning errors.
spec.hint_message: Panics: Unrecoverable errors trigger panic!. Stack unwinds, running Drop. catch_unwind() can recover. Set panic=abort in Cargo.toml to skip unwinding. Use sparingly - prefer Result for recoverable errors.

spec.name: Level 24 - Smart Pointers - Box<T>
spec.message: Enter the world of Smart Pointers with Box<T>! Box provides heap allocation for data that might be too large for the stack or when you need dynamic sizing. Essential for recursive data structures.
spec.hint_message: Box<T>: Heap allocation, single ownership. Box::new(value) creates, * dereferences. Enables recursive types like Box<Node>. Automatically derefs, so box.method() works like (*box).method().

spec.name: Level 34 - Custom Error Types
spec.message: Create meaningful error types! Implement the Error trait, use enums for multiple error variants, and provide useful context. Learn about error conversion and libraries like thiserror for ergonomic error handling.
spec.hint_message: Custom errors: Implement Error + Display + Debug. Use enums for variants. From trait enables ? operator conversions. thiserror crate simplifies error creation with derives.

spec.name: Level 20 - Error Handling Introduction
spec.message: Begin your journey into Rust's error handling philosophy! Learn when to panic vs return errors, basic Option<T> and Result<T, E> usage, and the difference between recoverable and unrecoverable errors.
spec.hint_message: Error handling: panic! for unrecoverable errors. Option<T> for nullable values: Some(T) or None. Result<T, E> for operations that can fail: Ok(T) or Err(E). Use match, unwrap(), or expect().

spec.name: Level 43 - Generics
spec.message: Write flexible, reusable code with Generics! Create functions, structs, and enums that work with multiple types. Learn type parameters, trait bounds, where clauses, and const generics.
spec.hint_message: Generics: <T> syntax for type parameters. Trait bounds: <T: Trait>. where clauses for complex bounds. Zero-cost: monomorphization creates specialized versions. Const generics: <const N: usize>.

spec.name: Level 30 - RAII Pattern
spec.message: Master RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)! This fundamental pattern ties resource lifetime to object lifetime. Resources are acquired in constructors and automatically released in destructors.
spec.hint_message: RAII: Resources tied to object lifetime. Acquire in new()/from(), release in Drop. Examples: File, Mutex, Vec. Guarantees cleanup even with panics. Scope-based resource management prevents leaks.

spec.name: Level 25 - Smart Pointers - Rc<T>
spec.message: Enable shared ownership with Rc<T> (Reference Counted)! When you need multiple owners of the same data, Rc tracks references and deallocates when the count reaches zero. Single-threaded only!
spec.hint_message: Rc<T>: Shared ownership via reference counting. Rc::new(value) creates, Rc::clone(&rc) increases count. Immutable only. Use Rc::strong_count() to check references. Drops when count = 0.

spec.name: Level 49 - Testing
spec.message: Ensure code quality with comprehensive testing! Master unit tests, integration tests, assert macros, and test organization. Learn property-based testing and mocking strategies.
spec.hint_message: Testing: #[test] attribute for unit tests, #[cfg(test)] for test modules. assert!, assert_eq!, assert_ne! macros. Integration tests in tests/ directory. cargo test runs all tests.

spec.name: Level 5 - Control Flow
spec.message: Master Rust's control flow! Use if expressions, loops (loop, while, for), and match expressions. Notice how if is an expression in Rust, not just a statement. Use doors to practice boolean logic!
spec.hint_message: Control flow: 'if condition { } else { }' returns values. 'loop { }' is infinite, 'while condition { }', 'for item in iterator { }'. 'match' is powerful pattern matching.

spec.name: Level 2 - Variables & Mutability
spec.message: Master Rust Variables & Mutability! 🔒 Navigate around obstacles to collect items about variables. Learn why Rust makes variables immutable by default - it prevents bugs and enables fearless concurrency. TO WIN: Collect both 'variables_tip' and 'mutability_tip' items, then grab the goal. This teaches memory safety without runtime cost!
spec.hint_message: RUST SYNTAX: 'let x = 5;' creates immutable variable (cannot change). 'let mut y = 10; y = 15;' creates mutable variable. Immutability by default prevents data races and makes code easier to reason about. Press B to see full documentation!

spec.name: Level 6 - Ownership Basics
spec.message: Welcome to Rust's most unique feature: Ownership! Understanding ownership is crucial for memory safety without garbage collection. Learn the three rules and how values move between scopes.
spec.hint_message: Ownership Rules: 1) Each value has one owner, 2) Only one owner at a time, 3) Value is dropped when owner goes out of scope. Assignment moves ownership by default.

spec.name: Level 35 - Error Propagation (?)
spec.message: Master error propagation with the ? operator! Learn to chain fallible operations elegantly, propagate errors up the call stack, and use libraries like anyhow for error context.
spec.hint_message: Error propagation: ? operator automatically returns Err or unwraps Ok. Works with Result and Option. main() can return Result. anyhow provides easy error context and chaining.

spec.name: Level 9 - Arrays & Tuples
spec.message: Explore compound data types! Arrays store multiple values of the same type with fixed size. Tuples group different types together. Both are stack-allocated and perfect for known-size collections.
spec.hint_message: Arrays: [T; N] syntax, fixed size. let arr = [1, 2, 3] or [0; 5]. Tuples: (T1, T2, T3) syntax, different types. Access with .0, .1, etc. or destructure with let (a, b, c) = tuple.

spec.name: Level 44 - Associated Types
spec.message: Master Associated Types in traits! Learn when to use associated types vs generics, projection syntax, and how they create cleaner APIs. Explore iterator patterns and higher-ranked trait bounds.
spec.hint_message: Associated types: 'type Item;' in traits. One implementation per type. Use when relationship is 1:1. Iterator::Item is classic example. <T as Trait>::AssociatedType for projection syntax.
